explanation:
For analyzing whether any operations in OS_TaskDelete_Impl are dead (i.e., executed but removable without changing behavior) the next agent needs the following symbols and why:

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Determines how the token is translated to an impl pointer (and whether NULL checks or side-effects exist). Removing the table access could change behavior if it performs checks or conversions.

- OS_impl_task_table
  - The backing table used by the macro; needed to know indexing/validity semantics and whether the lookup can fail or is a no-op.

- OS_impl_task_internal_record_t
  - Required to know the type and meaning of impl->id (e.g. pthread_t), and whether reading impl->id has side effects. Also needed to see if impl is guaranteed valid.

- OS_object_token_t
  - The token type is used to index the table; its layout or semantics may affect whether the lookup is meaningful/redundant.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  - Static graph shows this is used; its behavior determines whether the token->index conversion can be optimized away or elided, which impacts dead-code assessment of the table lookup and subsequent operations.

- pthread_cancel
  - The cancellation call has runtime effects (sends cancel request) and return semantics (0 on success, errno on failure). To know if the call is removable (dead) you must know its observable effects and failure modes.

- pthread_join
  - This blocks until thread exit and optionally stores the thread return value into the provided pointer. Its blocking behavior is a salient side effect; also the meaning of the second argument (can it be NULL?) is needed to judge whether storing the return value into retval is a dead operation.

- OS_DEBUG
  - The debug macro controls whether the formatted diagnostic calls (and their argument evaluations) are actually emitted. If OS_DEBUG is defined as a no-op that discards its arguments, the calls and their argument evaluations are effectively dead and can be removed without behavior change; if it evaluates arguments conditionally, those argument calls (ObjectIdFromToken/strerror) may or may not execute.

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken
  - Called inside the debug formatting; if debug is active these calls may have side effects or cost. If debug is inactive, they may not be evaluated. Need its semantics to decide if those calls are dead.

- OS_ObjectIdToInteger
  - Converts object id for debug output; same rationale as ObjectIdFromToken — whether it has side effects matters for dead-code determination.

- strerror
  - Converts error code to string; may be negligible but could be non-reentrant or have side effects in some implementations. Knowing its semantics is required to determine if the debug path has observable effects.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The function always returns this constant; include it to verify that removing/altering any of the above operations would not change the returned value (i.e., whether the operations are only diagnostic/side-effect-free and therefore dead).

These symbols together let the next agent determine (a) which operations have observable side effects (thread cancellation/joining, blocking), (b) which operations are purely diagnostic and possibly compiled out (OS_DEBUG and its argument evaluation), and (c) whether local stores (e.g., storing the join result into retval) are actually used — all necessary to decide if any executed operations are dead under the MISRA rule.
